		<div class="span8">
			<h4 class="blue" >3. Proper Relaxation (Savasana)</h4>
			<p class="paragraph">
				Yogic relaxation techniques not only relax the tensed and tired muscles but also relax the mind and reconcile you with the purpose of living.</p>
			<p class="paragraph">
				Many of us today suffer from a huge load of unacknowledged fatigue. We carry tension with us all day and do not know how to release it. We spend more energy keeping muscles in continuous readiness for work than in actually working usefully. We dissipate vital energy in anger, fear and negative emotions. Tiredness accumulates on a physical, mental and spiritual level, draining us of joy in our everyday lives. We run the risk of burning out our physical vehicle if we do not practice relaxation.</p>
			<p class="paragraph">
				The deep cause of stress is existential. Spiritual tension and fatigue come about from the underlying questions - who am I? What is my purpose here? What is the meaning of life?</p>
			<p class="paragraph">
				Yoga suggests we should not wait for a spiritual crisis to address our spiriutal needs and concerns. Gently exploring the questions we have about ourselves and our relationship to the universe brings a sense of deep relaxation which permeates all other aspects of our physical and mental wellbeing. Using the guidance of teachers, books, workshops, and satsang (company of the wise) we expand our understanding and fears and anxieties are replaced by faith, love, confidence and knowledge.
			</p>
		</div>
	</div>
	
