			<h4 class="blue" >5. Positive Thinking and Meditation</h4>
			<p class="paragraph">
				A car may have a new battery, a smoothly functioning cooling system, perfectly lubricated parts and a full gas tank. However, without a driver in full control of his/her senses and a road map to their destination, the vehicle is useless. Positive thinking and meditation allow us to assume the role of this driver in order to make full use of the physical body.</p>
			<p class="paragraph">
				Positive thinking begins with understanding the mind. By examining the nature of thoughts, we realize how we can choose and direct them for maximum happiness and effectiveness. Positive thinking is the preparation for meditation. A positive outlook on life can be developed by learning and practicing the teachings of the philosophy of Vedanta.</p>
			<p class="paragraph">
				The deep cause of stress is existential. Spiritual tension and fatigue come about from the underlying questions - who am I? What is my purpose here? What is the meaning of life?</p>
			<p class="paragraph">
				The purpose of meditation is to experience our true Self. Most of us have asked what we are doing here, what is our purpose or goal in life. Yoga says the answers are within. Meditation is a time and space set apart specifically  for no other purpose than to look within for these answers. The mind will be brought under perfect control by regular practice of meditation.
			</p>
